Categorical Variables for Clarity, Cut, and Color¶

Lists to specify the order for each of the three categorical variables

In [10]:
clarity_levels = ['I1', 'SI2', 'SI1', 'VS2', 'VS1', 'VVS2', 'VVS1', 'IF']
cut_levels = ['Fair', 'Good', 'Very Good', 'Premium', 'Ideal']
color_levels = ['J', 'I', 'H', 'G', 'F', 'E', 'D']

Using lists to communicate to Pandas the correct order for the levels of the three categorical variables

In [11]:
diamonds.cut = pd.Categorical(diamonds.cut, cut_levels)
diamonds.color = pd.Categorical(diamonds.color, color_levels)
diamonds.clarity = pd.Categorical(diamonds.clarity, clarity_levels)

Colors to serve as palettes to be used for visualizations later in the notebook

In [12]:
clarity_pal = ['lightpink', 'darkmagenta', 'mediumslateblue', 'steelblue', 
               'turquoise', 'darkseagreen', 'palegoldenrod', 'tomato']
cut_pal = ['lightpink', 'darkmagenta', 'mediumslateblue', 'steelblue', 'turquoise']
color_pal = ['lightpink', 'darkmagenta', 'mediumslateblue', 'steelblue', 'turquoise', 'darkseagreen', 'palegoldenrod']

Scatterplots of Price Against Carat¶

Exploring the relationship between the price and carat attributes by generating scatter plots

In [16]:
plt.figure(figsize = [8,6])
plt.scatter(x = diamonds['carat'], y = diamonds['price'], s = 20, alpha = 0.4, color = 'purple')
plt.xlabel('Carat Size')
plt.ylabel('Price(in $)')
plt.title('Relationship between Diamond Price and Carat Size')
plt.show()

Reproducing the plot from above, but will now color the points according to their clarity

In [17]:
plt.figure(figsize = [8,6])
for i in range(len(clarity_levels)):
    
    sel = np.array(diamonds['clarity'] == clarity_levels[i])
    
    plt.scatter(x = diamonds.carat[sel], y = diamonds.price[sel], s = 20, alpha = 0.4, 
                color = clarity_pal[i], label = clarity_levels[i])

plt.xlabel('Carat Size')
plt.ylabel('Price(in $)')
plt.title('Relationship between Diamond Price and Carat Size')
plt.legend()
plt.show()

separating the points for each of the eight clarity levels into its own subplot

In [18]:
plt.figure(figsize = [12,6])

count=1


for i in range(len(clarity_levels)):
    plt.subplot(2, 4, count)
    
    
    sel = np.array(diamonds.clarity == clarity_levels[i])
    
    plt.scatter(x=diamonds.carat[sel], y=diamonds.price[sel], alpha=0.4,
                color=clarity_pal[i])
    plt.title(clarity_levels[i])
    plt.xlim([0,4])
    plt.ylim([0, 20000])        
    plt.xlabel('Carat Size')
    plt.ylabel('Price(in $)')
    count += 1


plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

Logarithmic Transformations¶

Applying logarithmic transformations to the price and carat columns, and exploring the distribution of these transformed variables

In [19]:
diamonds.loc[:, 'ln_carat'] = np.log(diamonds.loc[:, 'carat'])
diamonds.loc[:, 'ln_price'] = np.log(diamonds.loc[:, 'price'])

Using histograms to explore the distribution of the diamond prices, and the log of the diamond prices

In [20]:
plt.figure(figsize = [12,4])
plt.subplot(1,2,1)
plt.hist(x = diamonds['price'], bins = 20, edgecolor = 'k', color = 'pink' )
plt.xlabel('price')
plt.ylabel('Count')
plt.title('Histogram of Prices')

plt.subplot(1,2,2)
plt.hist(x = diamonds['ln_price'], bins = 20, edgecolor = 'k', color = 'plum')
plt.xlabel('Natural Log of Price')
plt.ylabel('Count')
plt.title('Histogram of Log-Prices')



plt.show()

Using histograms to explore the distribution of the carat sizes, and the log of the carat sizes

In [21]:
plt.figure(figsize = [12,4])
plt.subplot(1,2,1)
plt.hist(x = diamonds['carat'], bins = 20, edgecolor = 'k', color = 'darkolivegreen')
plt.xlabel('Carat Size')
plt.ylabel('Count')
plt.title('Histogram of Carat Sizes')

plt.subplot(1,2,2)
plt.hist(x = diamonds['ln_carat'], bins = 20, edgecolor = 'k', color = 'olive')
plt.xlabel('Natural Log of Carat Sizes')
plt.ylabel('Count')
plt.title('Histogram of Log-Sizes')



plt.show()

Scatterplot of Transformed Variables¶

A scatterplot of ln_price against ln_carat, with points colored according to their clarity

In [22]:
plt.figure(figsize = [8,6])
for i in range(len(clarity_levels)):
    
    sel = np.array(diamonds['clarity'] == clarity_levels[i])
    
    plt.scatter(x = diamonds.ln_carat[sel], y = diamonds.ln_price[sel], s = 20, alpha = 0.4, 
                color = clarity_pal[i], label = clarity_levels[i])

plt.xlabel('Natural Log of Carat Size')
plt.ylabel('Natural Log of Price')
plt.title('Relationship between Log-Price and Log-Carat Size')
plt.legend()
plt.show()

Grouping by Cut¶

Creating a grouped DataFrame displaying the mean price and carat size for each cut level

In [23]:
gb_cut = diamonds.loc[:,['cut','price', 'carat']]
gb_cut = gb_cut.groupby('cut').mean()
gb_cut

Visualization of DataFrame grouped by cut

In [24]:
plt.figure(figsize = [12,4])

plt.subplot(1,2,1)
for i in gb_cut:
    plt.bar(gb_cut.index, gb_cut['price'], edgecolor = 'k', color = cut_pal)
    plt.xlabel('Cut')
    plt.ylabel('Mean Price')
    plt.title('Mean Price by Cut')

plt.subplot(1,2,2)
for i in gb_cut:
    plt.bar(gb_cut.index, gb_cut['carat'], edgecolor = 'k', color = cut_pal)
    plt.xlabel('Cut')
    plt.ylabel('Mean Carat Size')
    plt.title('Mean Carat Size by Cut')



plt.show()
